{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: collectors for metrics/issue tracker/deploy log must all feed the summarization input. This is not just one function’s pure logic; wiring bugs (missing source, overwritten field, wrong merge) appear when modules interact. Real OS/network is not required if each source adapter is stubbed in-process, and correctness does not depend on model output quality.","test_description":"Run the report assembly pipeline with three deterministic in-process source adapters returning distinct marker payloads; assert the exact payload sent to the summary-generation interface contains all three source sections/keys and none are dropped during merge.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior targets cross-module error propagation and fallback rendering: one source failure must map to section-level degradation while overall report generation continues. Unit is too low because the failure appears at boundary between source client, aggregator, and renderer. No real OS/network/subprocess is required to reproduce; deterministic failing stub is sufficient. No dependence on LLM quality.","test_description":"Wire report generation with two successful source adapters and one adapter that raises timeout/unavailable; assert process completes, output includes normal sections for available sources plus a `data unavailable` note in the failed section, and no global abort is raised.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.83,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model judgment/generation fidelity (whether summary preserves key values). A stubbed model would hide real hallucination/omission/misstatement failures. This is the deterministic-assertion trap: even if assertions are concrete, the risk is in non-deterministic LLM output quality.","test_description":"Invoke the real summary model on controlled input fixtures containing key numeric/status facts; evaluate whether generated narrative includes and correctly states required key values across repeated runs with acceptance thresholds for factual retention/accuracy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This requires real external infrastructure boundary: end-to-end delivery to an inbox depends on actual email transport behavior and service integration, which in-process fakes can hide. LLM output quality is not the asserted property here (delivery correctness is), so Agentic is not required for minimum failure detection.","test_description":"Execute scheduled run (or trigger equivalent) against test instances of the three data sources and real email delivery path to a test mailbox; assert message is received in inbox for configured recipient with expected subject/body sections and successful delivery status.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Rejected Workflow because behavior specifies one end-to-end delivery outcome, not multiple agentic decisions; rejected Agentic because assertion is